*Background:*
perforce allows two type of branching mechanism: "file branching" and "spec branching".
from p4 official documentation: [Codelines and Branching|https://www.perforce.com/perforce/doc.current/manuals/p4guide/chapter.codelines.html]:
{quote}You can create branches using file specifications or branch specifications. For simple branches, use file specifications. For branches that are based on complex sets of files or to ensure that you have a record of the way you defined the branch, use branch specifications. Branch specifications can also be used in subsequent integrations. Branch specifications also can serve as a record of codeline policy.{quote}

*Use Case*
Currently Fisheye perforce only supports "spec branching" (check developer comments in FE-933). Due to the fact that "file branching" is a more simple branching scheme and widely used by p4 users, fisheye should implement this support.

*Steps to reproduce:*

 * create a huge changeset with 100'000 files.
 * select the changeset from the activity tab - it takes > 10s to load
 * expand a tree - again it takes > 10s to expand a node
 * click between files - it takes > 10s to load the file

*Code analysis:*

 * we collect all files ("revisions") from a changeset and sort them, it takes ~5s to build a list and another ~5s to sort it; out of it we calculate currentPage and selectedIndex parameters

excerpt from com.cenqua.fisheye.web.changeset.ChangeSetPageData#ChangeSetPageData:

{code:java}
 // 1st slowness
        changeSet.visitRevisions(new Visitor<FileRevision>() {
            public void visit(FileRevision rev) {
                // rev.getRevInfoKey().getPath() gets the path without triggering a full load
                allChangesetFileRevisions.add(new PathAndRevId(rev.getRevInfoKey().getPath().getPath(), rev.getRevID()));
            }
        });

// 2nd slowness
        Collections.sort(allChangesetFileRevisions);
{code}

 * the ChangeSetPageData ("p") is called by LoadChangesetPageAjaxAction, which renders changesetPageAjaxResponse.jsp, which is called 3 times to render:
 ** entire page activity stream page
 ** directory tree
 ** file content

 * the changesetPageAjaxResponse.jsp uses stuff like p.repname, p.currentPage, p.selectedIndex etc

 * the directory tree has nodes with page number attached to each link, e.g.:

{code:xml}
<a href="/foo/changelog/svn-branches/dev/branch7/module1/abc.txt" class="fileLink ">
  abc.txt
  <input type="hidden" name="anchor" value="devZ002fbranch7Z002fmodule1Z002fabc.txt">
  <input type="hidden" name="page" value="3">
  <input type="hidden" name="index" value="1">
</a>
{code}

*Possible fix:*

1) while we cannot omit collecting and sorting of all revisions while rendering the entire tree, we could omit collecting and sorting these revisions when rendering the source page:
 * the page number parameter is already passed in the <a href> link clicked by a user
 * the selected index is always 0 for a source page
 * we don't use 'allChangesetFileRevisions' property for a source page

2) we could try to cache sorted results (as it won't change for a given changeset and we call it 3 times)

3) we could try to reduce amount of changesetFileRevisions collected when the directory tree is rendered - as we don't draw the entire tree at once - we could fetch data using extra ajax calls when user expands the dir node

